data.name: label4.Text
data.value: Listviews aren't really the best interface for lists of hundreds of thousands of item -- but there are situations where there is little other choice. Virtual lists are a means to handle lists of *many* items. The example below has 10,000,000 items. When editing rows, the serial # is not editable.

data.name: label5.Text
data.value: This is a simple file system explorer. It is *not* a namespace explorer -- it only handles files and directories. One interesting bit is accessing the Shell icon and type descriptions for files. If you choose an empty folder, you will see an example of an empty list message. Right clicking on the header will let you choose which columns are visible. The 'Attributes' column is an example of a FlagRenderer. You can save the current state of the view and restore it latter.

data.name: label1.Text
data.value: This list view shows the behaviour of the control when the absolute minimum of configuration has been done. In this case, each column has been told which aspect to display, and the birthday and hourly rate column have been given format strings. The Person and Occupation columns have minimum and maximum widths, Year of birth column is fixed width and Comments is free space filler. All of this configuration can be done within the IDE.

data.name: label2.Text
data.value: This list view has more customization, and shows what is possible with a few callbacks in place. It shows: owner drawn rendering; alternate line colouring; specialised group item counts (the 'Cooking Skill' and 'Birthday' columns); adding extra information to the 'Tile' view.

data.name: label3.Text
data.value: The DataListView (below) is sourced from the data table above. Changes to the data table are automatically reflected in the listview. DataListViews can operate on DataTables, DataViews or DataSets. This pane also shows RowFormatter callbacks. Put the words 'red', 'green', 'blue', 'italic' or 'bold' in a data field to see the formatter at work. It also shows animated GIFs in action.

data.name: label12.Text
data.value: The ListViewPrinter class makes printing a ListView ridiciously easy. The format of the report can be easily customised: the styles Minimal, Modern and Too Much! are just some examples. N.B The preview below is not a full print previewer -- it only shows the first two pages of the report.

data.name: label26.Text
data.value: This is a FastObjectListView, named because it trades functionality for speed. It does not support grouping; it cannot be put into Tile view, but otherwise it acts just like a normal ObjectListView -- only much faster!
